<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="85" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="85">
This species has a sinuous 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“m”">&quot;m&quot;</normalizedToken>
-shaped band on the hindwings. Unlike other species with similar pattern on the hindwings such as 
<taxonomicName genus="E." lsidName="E. memorans" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" rank="species" species="memorans">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">E. memorans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="E." lsidName="E. collusoria" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" rank="species" species="collusoria">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">E. collusoria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="E." lsidName="E. colubra" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" rank="species" species="colubra">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">E. colubra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in 
<taxonomicName genus="E." lsidName="E. serpentifera" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" rank="species" species="serpentifera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">E. serpentifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“m”">&quot;m&quot;</normalizedToken>
-shaped band does not reach the wing margin. 
<bibRefCitation author="Janzen, DH" journalOrPublisher="Entomological News" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" publicationUrl="http://janzen.sas.upenn.edu" refId="B20" refString="Janzen, DH, Hallwachs, W, 2009. Dynamic database for an inventory of the macrocaterpillar fauna, and its food plants and parasitoids, of Area de Conservacion Guanacaste (ACG), northwestern Costa Rica. http://janzen.sas.upenn.edu" title="Dynamic database for an inventory of the macrocaterpillar fauna, and its food plants and parasitoids, of Area de Conservacion Guanacaste (ACG), northwestern Costa Rica." url="http://janzen.sas.upenn.edu" year="2009">Janzen and Hallwachs (2009)</bibRefCitation>
reported 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. calocarpa" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" rank="species" species="calocarpa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">D. calocarpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName family="Menispermaceae" genus="D." lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" rank="family">Menispermaceae</taxonomicName>
) as its hostplant. Adults have been found feeding on 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. papaya" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" rank="species" species="papaya">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">C. papaya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName family="Caricaceae" genus="C." lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" rank="family">Caricaceae</taxonomicName>
) and 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rutaceae" genus="Citrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Citrus" order="Sapindales" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Citrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in Mexico (
<bibRefCitation author="Robinson, GS" journalOrPublisher="Biotropica" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" publicationUrl="http://www.nhm.ac.uk/hosts" refId="B28" refString="Robinson, GS, Ackery, PR, Kitching, IJ, Beccaloni, GW, Hernandez, LM, 2010. HOSTS - A Database of the World's Lepidopteran Hostplants. Natural History Museum, London. http://www.nhm.ac.uk/hosts" title="HOSTS - A Database of the World's Lepidopteran Hostplants. Natural History Museum, London." url="http://www.nhm.ac.uk/hosts" year="2010">Robinson et al. 2010</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3157/021.126.0511" author="Hernandez-Ruiz, A" journalOrPublisher="Entomological News" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" pagination="415 - 420" refId="B19" refString="Hernandez-Ruiz, A, Illescas-Riquelme, CP, Bautista-Martinez, N, Vargas-Abasolo, R, Valdez-Carrasco, J M, Figueroa-Castro, P, 2017. Identification of fruit-piercing moths (Lepidoptera: Erebidae) and damage caused to papaya fruit in Mexico. Entomological News 126 (5): 415 - 420, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3157/021.126.0511" title="Identification of fruit-piercing moths (Lepidoptera: Erebidae) and damage caused to papaya fruit in Mexico." url="https://doi.org/10.3157/021.126.0511" volume="126" year="2017">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Hernández-Ruiz">Hernandez-Ruiz</normalizedToken>
et al. 2017
</bibRefCitation>
). In Mexico, adults are active from April to November and are commonly collected with light traps (
<bibRefCitation author="Chame-Vasquez, ER" journalOrPublisher="Dugesiana" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" pagination="19 - 20" refId="B10" refString="Chame-Vasquez, ER, Jimenez, LN, 2009. Eudocima serpentifera (Walker, 1858). Lepidoptera: Noctuidae: Calpinae. Dugesiana 16 (1): 19 - 20" title="Eudocima serpentifera (Walker, 1858). Lepidoptera: Noctuidae: Calpinae." volume="16" year="2009">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Chamé-Vásquez">Chame-Vasquez</normalizedToken>
and Jimenez 2009
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="85" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="85">
Widely distributed in Tropical America. 
<bibRefCitation author="Walker, F" journalOrPublisher="Ceiba," pageId="0" pageNumber="85" pagination="983 - 1236" refId="B38" refString="Walker, F, 1858. List of the specimens of lepidopterous insects in the collection of the British Museum, 13. In: Trustees of the British Museum, London.: 983 - 1236" title="List of the specimens of lepidopterous insects in the collection of the British Museum, 13." volumeTitle="Trustees of the British Museum, London." year="1858">Walker ([1858])</bibRefCitation>
describes this species from the Dominican Republic and Brazil. Additionally, there are occasional records of this species from the southern United States (
<bibRefCitation author="Brou, Jr. VA" journalOrPublisher="Southern Lepidopterists News" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" pagination="105 - 108" refId="B7" refString="Brou, Jr. VA, 2006. A new US record for the tropical fruit-piercing moth Eudocima serpentifera (Walker, 1858). Southern Lepidopterists News 28: 105 - 108" title="A new US record for the tropical fruit-piercing moth Eudocima serpentifera (Walker, 1858)." volume="28" year="2006">Brou 2006</bibRefCitation>
). In Mexico, it occurs in an elevational range between 150 and 3000 m (
<bibRefCitation author="Chame-Vasquez, ER" journalOrPublisher="Dugesiana" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" pagination="19 - 20" refId="B10" refString="Chame-Vasquez, ER, Jimenez, LN, 2009. Eudocima serpentifera (Walker, 1858). Lepidoptera: Noctuidae: Calpinae. Dugesiana 16 (1): 19 - 20" title="Eudocima serpentifera (Walker, 1858). Lepidoptera: Noctuidae: Calpinae." volume="16" year="2009">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Chamé-Vásquez">Chame-Vasquez</normalizedToken>
and Jimenez 2009
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="85" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="85">This species is recorded for the first time from Colombia.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
